--Intuition

Start with the widest container (leftmost and rightmost lines)

Area is determined by:

width √ó min(height[left], height[right])


--To potentially get a larger area:

Move the pointer with the smaller height

Moving the taller one cannot increase the height and only reduces width

‚è± Complexity

Time: O(n)

Space: O(1)

This is optimal.
Brute force would be O(n¬≤), which is too slow.

üíª Java Solution (Optimal)
class Solution {
    public int maxArea(int[] height) {
        int left = 0;
        int right = height.length - 1;
        int maxArea = 0;

        while (left < right) {
            int h = Math.min(height[left], height[right]);
            int width = right - left;
            maxArea = Math.max(maxArea, h * width);

            // Move the pointer with smaller height
            if (height[left] < height[right]) {
                left++;
            } else {
                right--;
            }
        }

        return maxArea;
    }
}

üß™ Dry Run (Example 1)
height = [1,8,6,2,5,4,8,3,7]

left=0, right=8 ‚Üí area = 1√ó8 = 8
move left

left=1, right=8 ‚Üí area = 7√ó7 = 49 (max)
move right

Continue ‚Üí no larger area found
Return 49

üìå Key Insight (Interview Gold)

The area is limited by the shorter line, so moving the taller line never helps.
